messages.content: It's meant to be for audio coupling only, so no cables are needed.

The scheme has not been frozen yet, so if you have some input, please don't be shy and speak up. I had the crazy idea to make it an analog modem only, so instead of digital data in and digital data out, I thought about making it complex values in, and complex values out. This way we can play with a lot more waveforms, without having to deal with synchronization or equalization.
280 subcarriers  7.5 baud  code rate  log2(mod order)

I was thinking in the lines of: instead of completely removing the modes from the modem, we could signal the modes with a byte. The highest bit tells us either to interpret the signal as a known mode (for example your table) or the number of symbols, and then its simply the comlex values, without interpretation.

Because we shortened the guard interval, we now can have one more symbol squeezed in a 1 second frame. I intent to use that symbol to signal base37 call sign and the mode byte, so that even that doesn't need to be bothered with when simply wanting to send complex values for experimentation.
And this time I want to use a very short Polar(256, 71) code instead of a BCH(255, 71) code to get a faster soft decode.

I've also added the code rates 2/3, 3/4 and 5/6. I have not simulated if the code rates are good. just used approximate scaling of the Bhattacharyya parameter, derived from the 1/2 rate codes that I simulated a bit more.

Will now simulate the Polar codes with a couple of parameters lower and higher than the current ones an pick the ones that give us the best frame error rate curves for an unknown channel. With this Polar(65536, 43808) (2/3-rate) code it looks like the previous parameter of 0.28 was suboptimal. 0.27 works better, as it has a lower FER towards the SNR range it is supposed to be error free.
This is something that takes a long time to simulate, so it will be one code per day.
